communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Newcastle disease virus (NDv) is very versatile. Airborne aerosol infection occurs. Vaccinated birds can appear to be healthy while shedding virus, granted significantly less than unvaccinated infected birds; thus, you can have virus contaminated recycled-poultry meals; faecal contaminated containers, transport, and vacated poultry housing inadequately cleaned and disinfected ready to infect the incoming birds.

Back in the early 1970s Bill Allan and I with colleagues from Porton Down (Wiltshire, England) caught NDv 90 m downwind of infected housed poultry. Later with a different team we showed that the 1972 ND epizootic in county Antrim (Northern Ireland) came from feed stored in a warehouse in Rotterdam port (Netherlands), presumably from infected wild birds roosting in the warehouse. Tracing the probable source of outbreaks is important so as to maintain control, and proactively vaccinate.

The relevant papers are:
1. Hugh-Jones, ME, Allan WH, Dark FA, Harper GJ. The evidence for the airborne spread of Newcastle disease. J Hyg (Lond). 1973; 71: 325-39. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2130488/pdf/jhyg00080-0111.pdf
2. O'Donoghue K, Lomniczi B, McFerran B, et al. Retrospective characterization of Newcastle disease virus Antrim '73 in relation to other epidemics, past and present, Epidemiology & Infection, 132: 357-68". http://tinyurl.com/y83p57ov.
- Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5457167,37200.]
